## Scope

This slice adds the element geometry / placement / rotation domain as a
pure, headless‑testable layer in a new `Placement.fs` module, and reserves
the schema and project slots for it. It introduces no drawing code (Part C)
and no ray routing (Part B). The placement record, bounding box, two
normals, three rotations with per‑axis locks, catalogue‑kind tag, value‑id
slot, emission metadata, and the `toConstructorElement` mapping all land
here, together with the schema extension and the `OpticalConstructorProject`
extension for per‑element placement, proven by a round‑trip + schema‑validation
test.

The R1/R2/R3 scheme is dictated by how real optical mounts and stages are
built, not by mathematical convenience; the axes are modelled exactly rather
than as a fixed orthogonal triad.

## Requirements

### R-1. Element‑placement record (A.1)

A.1.1 A new module `Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Placement.fs`
MUST define an immutable F# record `ElementPlacement` holding, for one
on‑table element:
- `placementPoint` — the placement point in canonical meters on the table
  plane (see R-2);
- `r1`, `r2`, `r3` — the three rotation angles, each carried as the
  engine's `Angle` value so the existing angle constructors are reused, not
  re‑derived;
- `r1Locked`, `r2Locked`, `r3Locked` — three independent lock flags;
- `catalogueKind` — the UI‑facing catalogue kind (R-6);
- `valueId : string option` — the element value id (R-7);
- `box` — the bounding box (R-3);
- `displayUnit : Units.UnitOfMeasure` — the element's preferred display unit
  (display metadata only).

A.1.2 `r3Locked` MUST default to `true`; `r1Locked` and `r2Locked` MUST
default to `false` (R3 is locked by default and MUST be deliberately
unlocked before it can change).

### R-2. Placement point is the box centre (A.2)

A.2.1 The placement point MUST be defined as the centre of the element's
rectangular bounding box. Drawing, snapping (Part B), and slide bounds
(Part E) MUST all treat the placement point as the box centre, never an
edge or corner.

### R-3. Bounding box and the two normals (A.3)

A.3.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define a `BoundingBox` record with three
canonical‑meter extents `a1`, `a2`, `b` describing an `A × A × B` box: a
square `a1 × a2` face (with `a1 = a2` for the standard box) extruded by
depth `b` along the primary normal.

A.3.2 The box MUST carry **two normals**:
- **N1 — primary normal**, perpendicular to the `A × A` face. R1 spins
  about N1 (R1 and N1 coincide by definition).
- **N2 — secondary normal**, perpendicular to N1 in the element's rest
  pose.

A.3.3 **Rest pose.** When an element is placed without rotation
(R1 = R2 = R3 = 0), N1 MUST point along the central ray (and so along the
R1 axis) and N2 MUST point along the table normal. An unrotated element
faces the incoming beam squarely.

A.3.4 **Default box proportions by role.** The default box dimensions are a
spec‑author detail fixed here (concrete values, canonical meters). They are
guidance for recognisable schematic shapes, not physical dimensions:
- Optical elements (polarizers, sample, lens, mirrors) — thin and wide:
  face `A_O = 0.05 m`, depth `B_O = 0.01 m` (`A_O > B_O`).
- Light source — long and narrow: face `A_L = 0.025 m`, depth
  `B_L = 0.08 m` (`B_L > A_L`, and `A_O > A_L`, `B_L > B_O`).
- Detector — shaped like an optical element: `A_O × A_O × B_O`.
These defaults MUST live as named constants in `Placement.fs` so a single
edit restyles every element of a role.

### R-4. The three rotations and their frames (A.4)

A.4.1 **R1** MUST rotate the element about its surface normal N1. At normal
incidence the R1 axis coincides with the central ray; once R2 ≠ 0 the face
no longer faces the beam and the R1 axis is no longer the central ray — R1
still turns the element about its own face normal. R1 MUST NOT be treated
as a polarizer's azimuth (a polarizer's azimuth lies *in* the face; at rest
pose it is R2 that corresponds to the azimuth).

A.4.2 **R2** MUST rotate the element about the table normal. R2 is the tilt
that steers a beam within the table plane and is what decouples the R1 axis
from the central ray.

A.4.3 **R2 is measured from the incident ray, not from a fixed table
axis.** When an element sits on a ray that is not horizontal, the element's
own R2 MUST be applied relative to the direction of the incident ray. The
table‑frame rotation of an element whose incident ray already makes angle
`r2` with the horizontal and whose own dialled tilt is `R2` MUST therefore
equal `r2 + R2`. `Placement.fs` MUST expose a pure function that, given the
incident‑ray direction and the element's `r2`, returns the element's
table‑frame orientation; this function MUST satisfy the `r2 + R2` additive
law.

A.4.4 **R3** MUST rotate the element about the third box axis (the
`N1 × N2` direction). When R3 ≠ 0 the three axes are no longer a fixed
orthogonal triad and **R1 is no longer perpendicular to R2** — the
placement math MUST follow the element's mount, not assume orthogonality.

A.4.5 **Per‑axis lock.** Each rotation MUST be independently lockable and
unlockable, freezing it at its current value. A locked rotation MUST ignore
any change request (Part E rotation gestures are inert while the targeted
axis is locked).

### R-5. Catalogue kind tag (A.5)

A.5.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define a `CatalogueKind` discriminated union with
exactly the catalogue roles of Part F (Light Source, Linear Polarizer,
Circular Polarizer, Sample, Lens, Flat Mirror, Curved Mirror, Detector).

A.5.2 `Placement.fs` MUST define a pure total function
`toConstructorElement : CatalogueKind -> ConstructorElement` mapping each
catalogue kind to its existing domain case (BeamTree.fs:35): Light Source →
`Source`; **both** Linear Polarizer and Circular Polarizer → `Polarizer`
(BeamTree.fs:37) — a polarizer is a polarizer regardless of placement, and
linear vs circular is a catalogue‑kind distinction, not a new domain case;
Sample → `Sample`; Lens → `Lens`; Flat Mirror → `FlatMirror`; Curved
Mirror → `CurvedMirror`; Detector → `Detector`. The existing `Analyzer`
case (BeamTree.fs:42) MUST NOT be surfaced as a catalogue kind and MUST be
left untouched (no domain‑DU removal in this spec).

### R-6. Element value id slot (A.6)

A.6.1 The `valueId : string option` field (R-1) MUST be present in the
schema and the placement record from the first build, and MUST be `None`
for every element the first build creates. It identifies the concrete
device or material behind an element's role (e.g. which laser an `LS` is,
which material a `Sample` is); the binding of a concrete id is deferred
(Part F commits only the menu action and an empty modal). Reserving the id
now fixes it in the schema so nothing is retro‑fitted later, and it is one
of the drawer's inputs from the start (Part C) so per‑device looks can be
added later without rewiring placement or ray logic.

### R-7. Ray‑group emission metadata (A.7)

A.7.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define per‑element emission metadata recording
whether the element emits its reflected ray group, its transmitted ray
group, or both. The invariant MUST be: an element MAY suppress its
reflected group **or** its transmitted group but **never both** — turning
the second one off MUST automatically turn the other back on. This MUST be
enforced by a smart constructor that cannot represent the both‑off state.

A.7.2 A mirror's default placement MUST suppress transmission (consistent
with the existing mirror rule that a mirror carries the reflected branch
only — `BeamNode.attach`, BeamTree.fs:74). Every non‑mirror element MUST be
placed emitting whatever its catalogue kind is configured to emit
(by default both).

### R-8. Schema and project extensions (A.8)

A.8.1 The project schema
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json`)
MUST be extended so that placement (the R-1 record, including box, normals
basis, three angles, three lock flags, catalogue kind, value id, emission
metadata, display unit) is representable. The `constructorElement` `$def`
is currently permissive (`true`, schema file `:201`); placement MUST be
added as a sibling of the per‑node element data without renaming any of the
nine reserved anchors (Project.fs:42).

A.8.2 The project aggregate `OpticalConstructorProject` (Project.fs:26)
MUST be extended to carry the table (Part C) and per‑element placement, so
that an opened project shows every element where it was left. The placement
data MUST round‑trip through the existing serialization
(ProjectFile.fs:20/:31) and pass schema validation
(SchemaValidation.fs:61) with no new serialization library. *(The table
portion of this extension is delivered by slice 004; this slice delivers the
per‑element placement portion.)*

### R-9. Reuse before invention (A.9)

For angles use the engine's existing `Angle` type and its constructors
rather than introducing a new angle type. For canonical‑meter values reuse
the `Units` conversions (Units.fs:43/:71). Add placement as a new record in
a new `Placement.fs` module rather than overloading `BeamNode`
(BeamTree.fs:53) with a flag‑heavy spatial payload — placement is a
distinct concern from beam‑tree topology.

## Non-requirements

- No drawing code (Part C / slice 004) and no ray routing (Part B / slice 002).
- No removal of the `Analyzer` domain case (BeamTree.fs:42).
- No real device/material picker behind the value id (Part F / slice 006).
- No schema migration / version‑upgrade code (0.6).
- The table representation and the `OpticalConstructorProject` table field
  are owned by slice 004, not this slice.

